The invariant patterns extracted (the “atoms”)

Invariant 1 — State

Every framework begins by admitting: the system has state (stocks, distributions, internal variables), and behavior is state evolution.
(GST open systems; SD/cybernetics; CAS.)  ￼

Invariant 2 — Constraints / Invariants

Systems survive by not violating certain constraints (homeostasis, conservation-like limits, viability bounds). Control is just constraint maintenance under disturbance.  ￼

Invariant 3 — Feedback (negative + positive)
	•	Negative feedback stabilizes (regulation).
	•	Positive feedback amplifies (growth, cascades).
Most interesting dynamics come from multiple coupled loops + delays.  ￼

Invariant 4 — Information + Noise

Action depends on signals, which are always noisy, delayed, filtered, and compressible only to limits.
Any “governance” system is partly a communications system.  ￼

Invariant 5 — Compression / Representation

Every system runs on a model (explicit or implicit). It must compress the world into manageable variables, or it can’t act fast enough. (This is the bridge between Shannon-style compression and “meaning compression.”)  ￼

Invariant 6 — Adaptation under novelty

If the environment changes, the system must update. CAS frames this explicitly: persistence requires continued adaptation to novelty.  ￼

Invariant 7 — Multi-scale emergence

Macro behavior ≠ micro intent. Macro patterns emerge from local interactions, and then macro conditions feed back to shape micro incentives/behavior.  ￼

Invariant 8 — Equifinality / Path multiplicity

There are typically many trajectories to the same attractor/outcome; what matters is constraints + feedback structure, not one privileged path.  ￼

Invariant 9 — Selection / Replication dynamics

Behaviors/strategies/ideas that pay off replicate more; population distributions shift. Replicator dynamics is the clean mathematical form of this.  ￼

Invariant 10 — Topology matters (networks)

Spread, fragility, and influence are shaped by connectivity; hubs change everything; preferential attachment yields heavy tails.  ￼

⸻

The “unified lens” in one sentence

Complex systems are constraint-maintaining state machines that steer via feedback, learn via selection, and coordinate via lossy/noisy information flowing across a topology and multiple scales.  ￼

